I enjoyed the course content, but I felt that most, if not all of it, was concerned with citations. I wish that the course had provided more information on strategies and tools to structure the different writings we did over the course duration. Although the samples were good guidance, I would have liked to see more strategies to help writers organize their writing; maybe using the different paragraphs they discussed in one of the modules only. I felt that the writing assessment criteria was poorly constructed, only related to the formatting of the writing, and not focusing on paragraphing or evidencing ideas, even though the writing instructions did specify a certain minumun number of paragraphs, sentences, and citations per paragraph.

It was an informative course but I faced difficulties getting the certificate. Some like, the task for peer evaluation requires evaluating minimum 3 submissions but so many submissions weren't available.

It helps you build your essay-writing muscles gradually.  Too much emphasis on plagiarism.  Some flaws in the grading forms.  The level of the participants is quite mixed, most feedback they give is useless ("good").

I expected the course to be more advanced than this. This course is suitable for a person who wants to start writing an essay for the first time. It is not suitable for people who have already written several peer-review essays.

The course was in-depth and a great learning experience. However, there should be a better way to conduct the peer-graded assignments. After rating a peer's assignment; one must provide the reason for giving them that grade. This will help the learner immensely. Also; there are people whose essays have not been graded for days. A system must be ensured where a person's assignment is graded ( auto or manually) within 2-3 days of submission. Otherwise, this course is great :)

1) Course content not systematic and sophisticated enough. 2) The lecturer seems not qualified or knowledgeable enough about the course topic. e.g. Regarding the MLA Works Cited format, she only gave some limited examples, without explaining it clearly.3) The quiz’s are not designed well, for the course owner simply copied a number of existing flash/video quiz’s embedded in between the lectures, which are not of high quality. Besides, the quiz’s at the end of each lecture are to short and too facile/easy. 4) The course depends hugely on peer review, but I don't get as much as I expected from it, partly because the grading standards are not well designed.

The course is well structured to help a learner; however the evaluation on this course is poor. The instructor would be able to give feedback to student who are struggling and helping them understanding the way to correct their mistake. While that can be challenging for an online class that have many registered students at the same time, student should be invited for a live conference where different essays with common mistakes are being corrected and student can ask questions. Another remark is the guide for evaluation, that should be reviewed and updated to a guide that is in correspondence with the objectives of the course.

There is always something new to learn. In this course, I enjoyed the lesson on plagiarism the most. I appreciate the use of MLA style for the assignments. However, I noticed that there were at least four peers (among those whose works were "assigned" to me for review) who were not very serious with the assignments they turned in. But all in all, the course was a very pleasant learning experience. It would have been perfect if we were able to consult the teacher via email even once. But I guess that is too much to ask for a free course. Thank you, Coursera and DOST Caraga!

The Advanced Writing Course offered by the University of California, Irvine was a very detailed and comprehensive learning to enhance student's writing and research skills. The modules started from argument essays, gave a deep insight on plagiarism cases,explained Synthesis essays and lastly concluded with the Advanced documented essays. The course was designed in a beautiful way since it gave clarity on all aspects of writing and also gave an insight into the formatting part of the essays.My only feedback for the course for further improvement would be that the assignments submitted should once also be reviewed by the faculty since many students require personal attention and honest guidance on how to improvise their writing skills.Overall it is a very engaging and interesting course as the learners are taught through practical real life cases to understand the topics better. Overall, the course shared many pointer of academic writing which were significant and research focused which is what makes it effective.

This course has good content and the lecturers
are good at explaining the subject clearly. I learned many things I didn't knew
before. But the only drawback I find in this course is peer graded assignments.
There is no involvement of teachers to review students works. Only students
review each others works and sometimes it takes a lot of time to get yourself a
review. Furthermore, one student has to review 3 other assignments in order to
complete one week. But sometimes, you won't see others' assignments and have to
check back many times to find others' assignments. So, that's a big weakness I
find in this course. Moreover, there is no community discussion forum for this
course. So, it is also lacking here. Overall, I find this course very helpful
but, it would be better if the creators can fix above mentioned problems. Thank
you!
